Lymphadenopathy, thrombocytopenia, and thromboembolic disease can be caused by several conditions, including autoimmune disorders, infections, and certain types of cancer. Hyperglycemia is a symptom of diabetes. Polycythemia is a condition in which there is too much red blood cell mass in the blood. 
Here are some of the possible causes of these symptoms:

* **Autoimmune disorders:** These are conditions in which the bodys immune system attacks its own cells and tissues. Some autoimmune disorders that can cause lymphadenopathy, thrombocytopenia, and thromboembolic disease include systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis (RA), and antiphospholipid syndrome (APS).
* **Infections:** Some infections, such as HIV/AIDS, Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and cytomegalovirus (CMV), can also cause these symptoms.
* **Cancer:** Some types of cancer, such as lymphoma and leukemia, can also cause these symptoms.
* **Diabetes:** Hyperglycemia is a symptom of diabetes, a condition in which the body does not produce enough insulin or does not use insulin properly.
* **Polycythemia:** This is a condition in which there is too much red blood cell mass in the blood. Polycythemia can be caused by a number of factors, including high altitude, smoking, and certain medications.

It is important to see a doctor if you are experiencing these symptoms. A doctor will be able to determine the underlying cause of your symptoms and recommend the appropriate treatment.
